<% content_for :title, "HTTP API" %>
<% content_for :meta_description, "Reference for the Logister ingest and check-in HTTP endpoints." %>
<% content_for :canonical_path, docs_http_api_path %>
<% content_for :og_type, "article" %>
<% content_for :json_ld, json_ld({
  "@context" => "https://schema.org",
  "@type" => "TechArticle",
  "name" => "Logister HTTP API",
  "url" => absolute_url_for(docs_http_api_path),
  "description" => "Reference for the Logister ingest and check-in HTTP endpoints."
}) %>

<div class="docs-page">
  <section class="docs-hero docs-hero-compact">
    <div>
      <p class="hero-kicker">Documentation / HTTP API</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Send events and check-ins over HTTP.</h1>
      <p class="hero-copy">
        Logister exposes project-scoped ingest endpoints for application events and heartbeat-style check-ins.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="docs-shell docs-layout">
    <div class="docs-rail">
      <%= render "sidebar" %>
    </div>

    <article class="<%= docs_article_classes %>">
      <section class="docs-article-header not-prose">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">API overview</p>
        <h2>Use the HTTP API when you are integrating directly.</h2>
        <p class="docs-lead">
          Most clients will use the Ruby guide or the CFML guide, but the API itself is simple: authenticate
          with a project token, then POST JSON to the right endpoint.
        </p>
        <div class="docs-outline-grid">
          <section class="docs-outline-card">
            <h3 class="docs-outline-title">Use this guide when:</h3>
            <ul class="docs-outline-list">
              <li>You are sending events from a custom client.</li>
              <li>You want the exact endpoint and payload shapes.</li>
              <li>You are debugging ingestion outside the app-specific guides.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <aside class="docs-outline-card">
            <h3 class="docs-outline-title">Keep nearby</h3>
            <ul class="docs-outline-list">
              <li>Your project API token</li>
              <li>Your Logister base URL</li>
              <li>One sample app event to send first</li>
            </ul>
          </aside>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="authentication" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Authentication</p>
        <h2>Use a project API token.</h2>
        <p>Send the token with either of these headers:</p>
        <ul class="docs-list">
          <li><code>Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;</code></li>
          <li><code>X-Api-Key: &lt;token&gt;</code></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="payload-shape" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Payload shape</p>
        <h2>Send nested payloads with an <code>event</code> or <code>check_in</code> root key.</h2>
        <p>
          The ingest controller requires an <code>event</code> payload, and the check-in controller requires a
          <code>check_in</code> payload. Keep your first request explicit and structured so you can verify the shape easily.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="ingest-events" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Ingest events</p>
        <h2>POST application events to the ingest endpoint.</h2>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "POST /api/v1/ingest_events",
          "Authorization: Bearer <token>",
          "Content-Type: application/json"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-bash", shell: true, aria_label: "Copy ingest endpoint example") %>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "{",
          "  \"event\": {",
          "    \"event_type\": \"error\",",
          "    \"level\": \"error\",",
          "    \"message\": \"NoMethodError in CheckoutService\",",
          "    \"fingerprint\": \"checkout-nomethoderror\",",
          "    \"occurred_at\": \"2026-02-14T12:00:00Z\",",
          "    \"context\": {",
          "      \"environment\": \"production\",",
          "      \"request_id\": \"abc123\",",
          "      \"metadata\": {",
          "        \"user_id\": 42",
          "      }",
          "    }",
          "    }",
          "  }",
          "}"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-json", aria_label: "Copy ingest payload example") %>
        <p>
          For database load metrics from the Ruby gem, metric events typically use <code>message: "db.query"</code> and
          include timing fields like <code>duration_ms</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>sql</code> in context.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="check-ins" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Check-ins</p>
        <h2>POST monitor heartbeats for scheduled work.</h2>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "POST /api/v1/check_ins",
          "Authorization: Bearer <token>",
          "Content-Type: application/json"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-bash", shell: true, aria_label: "Copy check-in endpoint example") %>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "{",
          "  \"check_in\": {",
          "    \"slug\": \"nightly-reconcile\",",
          "    \"status\": \"ok\",",
          "    \"expected_interval_seconds\": 900,",
          "    \"environment\": \"production\",",
          "    \"release\": \"2026.03.02\"",
          "  }",
          "}"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-json", aria_label: "Copy check-in payload example") %>
      </section>

      <section id="event-types" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Event types</p>
        <h2>Use the right event type for the data you are sending.</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Typical use</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>error</code></td>
              <td>Unhandled exceptions and captured failures</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>transaction</code></td>
              <td>Request timings and method latency</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>metric</code></td>
              <td><code>db.query</code> and custom timing metrics</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>log</code></td>
              <td>Structured application logs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>check_in</code></td>
              <td>Heartbeat-style scheduled job reporting</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          Transaction events work best when context includes <code>transaction_name</code>, <code>duration_ms</code>,
          and correlation fields like <code>trace_id</code> or <code>request_id</code>. Log events should carry the
          same identifiers when available so error views can pivot to surrounding logs cleanly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="verify-delivery" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Verify delivery</p>
        <h2>Make sure your first payload shows up where you expect.</h2>
        <p>
          Send one known-good payload first, then check the matching project in Logister before broadening the rollout.
          That gives you a clean baseline for authentication, endpoint selection, and event shape.
        </p>
        <%= docs_output_block([
          "1. Send one test error or transaction payload",
          "2. Open the matching project in Logister",
          "3. Confirm the event appears in the inbox or activity feed",
          "4. Inspect context fields to verify the payload shape",
          "5. Only then add the rest of your instrumentation"
        ].join("\n"), label: "Delivery verification") %>
        <div class="docs-note docs-note-tip not-prose">
          <strong>Next step</strong>
          <p>If you are integrating from CFML or Ruby, switch back to those guides once the raw HTTP path is working.</p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
